I apologize for the oversight. To fix the issue and make the moon appear completely dark when eclipsed, we can update the CSS further. Here's the updated code:

```css
:root {
    --bg-color: #2c2c2c;
    --light-color: #fdf8db;
    --button-color: #5a5a5a;
    --window-bg: #1a1a1a;
    --star-color: #c3c3b9;
}

/* ... (previous CSS code) ... */

.moon {
    position: absolute;
    top: 20px;
    left: 70px;
    width: 40px;
    height: 40px;
    background-color: var(--light-color);
    border-radius: 50%;
    overflow: hidden;
    animation: moon-eclipse 10s linear infinite;
}

.moon::before,
.moon::after {
    content: '';
    position: absolute;
    top: 0;
    left: 0;
    width: 40px;
    height: 40px;
    border-radius: 50%;
}

.moon::before {
    background-color: var(--light-color);
    animation: moon-cover 10s linear infinite;
}

.moon::after {
    background-color: var(--bg-color);
    animation: moon-cover 10s linear infinite;
    animation-delay: 5s;
}

@keyframes moon-eclipse {
    0% {
        transform: translateX(0);
    }
    100% {
        transform: translateX(100px);
    }
}

@keyframes moon-cover {
    0% {
        transform: translateX(0);
    }
    100% {
        transform: translateX(-100px);
    }
}
```

The main changes are:

1. Added two additional pseudo-elements, `.moon::before` and `.moon::after`, to create the eclipse effect.
2. The `.moon::before` element represents the light portion of the moon, and it moves in the opposite direction to the `.moon` element, creating the eclipse effect.
3. The `.moon::after` element represents the dark portion of the moon, and it moves in the same direction as the `.moon` element, but with a 5-second delay, ensuring the moon appears completely dark when eclipsed.

This should now create a more realistic eclipse effect, where the moon appears to be completely dark when it's eclipsed.

